---
title: Cross-Over Chickpea and Spinach Curry with Cooling Coriander
description: The male members of the HelloFresh Farm are reliably informed that there is a certain category of clothing called “cross-over” clothing. Arnie thought this might have something to do with his occasional penchant for high heels, but Caroline tells us they are clothes which can be worn from day to night. That got us to thinking about cross-over dishes - warm enough for the chilly nights we’re still having, but with a hint of impending Spring. This nutritious little number is the perfect addition to your nutritional closet.
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/54cf98a16ced6e52188b456a.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipecards/card/54cf98a16ced6e52188b456a.pdf
course: main course
servings: 2
time required: 30 minutes
cuisine: Indian
nutrition:
  calories: 550 kcal
  fat: 8 g
  saturated fat: 2 g
  carbohydrates: 89 g
  protein: 29 g
author: HelloFresh
source: https://www.hellofresh.co.uk/recipes/cross-over-chickpea-and-spinach-curry-54cf98a16ced6e52188b456a
---

Peel and finely dice @onion{1}(quartered, 1/4 finely diced and 3/4 roughly chopped). Peel the @ginger{1}(peeled and grated or finely diced) with the edge of a #spoon{} and then grate or finely dice it. Finely chop the @garlic cloves{2}(finely chopped). Stab the @red chilli{1}(whole) a few times with the tip of a sharp #knife{} (to release the flavour).

Heat @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a pan on medium-low heat. Once hot, add the roughly chopped onion and cook for ~{5%minutes} (until soft). Add the garlic and cook for a further ~{1-2%minutes}. Add the @curry powder{2%tsp} and ginger and cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} to develop the flavour.

Cut the @vine tomatoes{2}(chopped) in half, remove the seeds (and discard) and roughly chop. Add the drained @chickpeas{1%400g can}(@drained), whole chilli and the chopped tomatoes to the pan. Add 1/2 the @vegetable stock pot{1} with @water{100%ml}, @salt{1/2%tsp} and a few grinds of @pepper{a few grinds}. Cook over a medium heat for ~{15%minutes}.

Heat @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a pan over a medium heat. Once hot add the finely diced onion and cook for ~{5%minutes}, or until soft.

Add the @basmati rice{200%g} to the pan and coat in the oil then add @water{300%ml}. Add the remaining half of the stock pot, @ground cinnamon{1/2%stick} and the @bay leaf{1}. Cover with a tight fitting #lid{} and cook on the lowest heat for ~{10%minutes} and then leave off the heat for ~{10%minutes} - don't peek under the lid until 20 mins are up!

Finely chop the @coriander{1/2%bunch}(finely chopped) and mix half with the @Greek style natural yoghurt{1/2%cup}(mixed) along with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{pinch}.

When the curry is cooked, take off the heat and stir through the @baby spinach{1/2%bag}.

Serve the curry on top of the basmati rice along with the yoghurt and top with the remaining chopped coriander.